<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: COMPROMISE SET ON HISTORIC HOMES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After a five-year battle over saving historic homes in Redondo Beach, the City 
Council has decided on a compromise approach that would raise barriers to quick 
demolition but ultimately allow owners to tear down and replace them. 
</P>
<P>
City officials have decided to create an eight-member Preservation Commission, 
effective Sept. 1. Under the measure, owners of buildings deemed to have 
unusual historic and architectural significance will be temporarily forestalled 
from demolishing, relocating or substantially altering their exteriors without 
the commission's approval. 
</P>
<P>
The protection covers only single-family homes that have been designated as 
landmarks or are in a historic district, and expires after 225 days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
