<SECTION>
<P>
Food; Part 8; Page 50; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1594 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOOD AND COMMON SENSE: THERE ARE LEANER AND LIGHTER ALTERNATIVES FOR BACK-YARD 
BARBECUES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JEAN MAYER and JEANNE GOLDBERG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
We hate to risk being accused of raining on that great American institution, 
the summer barbecue. But as nutritionists, we must point out that hamburgers 
and frankfurter, accompanied by macaroni, potato salad and potato chips -- the 
stuff of traditional barbecues -- are best reserved for a very occasional 
treat. 
</P>
<P>
But hold on, and don't put the grill in storage: Believe it or not, you can 
find culinary happiness in alternatives that are lower in fat, calories and 
sodium. 
</P>
<P>
These leaner, lighter choices begin with a focus on chicken and fish, both 
excellent candidates for the outdoor grill. For chicken, the key to variety 
lies in marinades that extend well beyond the usual sauces (invariably some 
shade of red) sold in the supermarket. 
</P>
<P>
One favorite, reminiscent of the Caribbean, is a mixture of oil, lime juice and 
minced onion seasoned with tarragon and hot pepper sauce. Teriyaki sauce, 
seasoned with a little brown sugar and mixed with a few drops of sesame oil, 
white vinegar and mustard is another good option to brush onto chicken. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
An Indian Touch 
</P>
<P>
For a marinade of chicken legs with an Indian touch, season one-quarter cup 
each of lemon juice and oil with six cloves of minced garlic, one tablespoon 
minced ginger root, one tablespoon ground cumin and several generous dashes of 
hot pepper sauce. Indeed, it is possible to grill anything from chunks of white 
meat on skewers or pounded breast, brushed lightly with oil, to quarters with 
the bone left in. To get the job done more quickly, precook chicken in the 
microwave oven. 
</P>
<P>
For fish, the sheer variety of choices, including shellfish such as shrimp and 
scallops, and the different combinations of herbs are all you need to create an 
endless parade of tastes. The teriyaki mixture we've suggested for chicken goes 
equally well on fish, especially tuna steaks and bluefish. The flavor of salmon 
steaks may be enhanced with sprinklings of thyme, sage, parsley and pepper 
before grilling. If you want to serve it with a sauce, try yogurt with plenty 
of minced cucumber folded in and seasoned with dill, grated onion and white 
pepper. 
</P>
<P>
Rosemary, lavender leaves, crushed fennel and cumin seeds are another good herb 
blend for seasoning fish. And, of course, in the summer months nothing is 
better than fresh, chopped basil. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Mayonnaise Alternatives 
</P>
<P>
As for accompaniments, our program begins with a farewell to mayonnaise. Yes, 
it does a nice job of holding potatoes, macaroni, cole slaw and even rice 
together, but at around 100 calories a tablespoon, it's a good idea to seek 
alternatives. A delicious side dish to go along with chicken is a lentil salad, 
popular in France in the summer but rarely seen here. To prepare it, a cup of 
lentils, providing six servings, is cooked with an onion stuck with two cloves 
and a bay leaf until tender. They are then drained, tossed with a minced onion, 
about two tablespoons each of oil and wine vinegar, chopped parsley, a little 
salt and freshly ground black pepper. 
</P>
<P>
A rice salad is another neglected option. Cooked rice is simply tossed with a 
little oil, lemon juice or wine vinegar, minced parsley and green onions. If 
you want more volume for calories, extend the salad by adding sliced water 
chestnuts, blanched bean sprouts and some lightly cooked green beans. You might 
also try seasoning it with cilantro, or Chinese parsley leaves. 
</P>
<P>
We also recommend a French potato salad, prepared by tossing sliced, small 
cooked potatoes with white wine vinegar, a little oil, and seasoning it with 
chopped parsley, chives and tarragon. 
</P>
<P>
Grilled vegetables are an increasingly popular feature at barbecues, and that 
is all to the good. Easily cooked on skewers or in pans specially designed for 
the task (or sometimes right on the grill itself), they require only a slight 
brush of oil and, if desired, a strategically chosen herb or two. At a cost of 
very few calories they provide taste, color and texture, not to mention 
vitamins, minerals and fiber. If you'd rather stick to raw vegetables such as 
carrot sticks and pepper rings, or even raw broccoli and cauliflower, try a dip 
made by adding a teaspoon of curry powder to a cup of low-fat yogurt. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
In Favor of Fruit 
</P>
<P>
For dessert, we strongly favor fresh fruit. But if you're in the mood for 
something more elaborate than a watermelon slice or a bowl of cherries, we 
suggest fruit lightly poached in a syrup of equal parts of sugar and water. Our 
favorites include nectarines, apricots or peaches served with a puree of 
raspberries or strawberries. And if you're feeling extra fancy, a small bit of 
liqueur goes a long way toward enhancing the flavor. 
</P>
<P>
As you can see, it's well within your grasp to eat festive, outdoor meals 
without either throwing nutritional principles out the window or sacrificing 
the great tastes of summer. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Metamucil Fares Well in Cholesterol Study 
</P>
<P>
Question: I recently heard on the radio that a "bulking agent" commonly used to 
promote normal bowel movements also lowers cholesterol. Is that true? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Results of recent studies do suggest that psyllium hydrophilic 
mucilloid, more familiar as Metamucil, does lower serum cholesterol. Psyllium 
is a water-soluble, gel-forming fiber derived from the husks of blond psyllium 
seeds. It belongs to a group of soluble fibers that include gums, pectins, 
mucilages and certain hemicelluloses that have been shown to lower serum 
cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
In the trial reported most recently, a group of men and women with mild to 
moderate elevation of serum cholesterol were placed on the National Cholesterol 
Education Program's "Step One Diet" to reduce serum cholesterol. On that diet, 
30% of the calories come from fat, 55% from carbohydrate and 15% from protein. 
It provides no more than 300 milligrams of cholesterol daily. 
</P>
<P>
After 12 weeks, subjects judged appropriate to the trial were divided into two 
groups. One group was given packets of Metamucil, the other an inert cellulose 
fiber. They were instructed to take the fiber in water three times a day before 
meals. 
</P>
<P>
The group adhered to the regimen remarkably well. Compared to those who 
received the inert fiber, subjects who took the psyllium achieved an additional 
reduction of almost 5% in total cholesterol level, and an 8% reduction in 
low-density lipoprotein associated with increased risk of heart attack. 
Moreover, the use of psyllium did not have adverse effects on other important 
health indicators, among them blood pressure, blood sugar levels and HDL 
cholesterol levels, associated with decreased risk of heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
Some subjects did suffer mild gastrointestinal complaints, but these were 
considered transient and minor. None was serious enough to require 
discontinuation of treatment. 
</P>
<P>
The authors of this study, which was conducted at the Hennepin County Medical 
Center in Minneapolis, Minn., were frank to point out that the amount of 
soluble fiber can be increased by diet, and they emphasize that the psyllium 
seed was used in addition to a diet for lowering serum cholesterol. The 
decision to use Metamucil as a cholesterol-lowering adjunct to your diet should 
be made only after a discussion with your physician to determine if it is 
appropriate. 
</P>
<P>
Q: Can you tell me how to choose one of the "preferred" margarines, if one is 
trying to control serum cholesterol? 
</P>
<P>
A: The nutrition-labeling panel is the best guide. Directly below the number of 
grams per serving, on most margarines you will find two other numbers. The 
number next to the "p" is for the amount of polyunsaturated fat it contains; 
the "s" is for the amount of saturated fat. To select those you describe as 
"preferred," choose among the many options where the amount of polyunsaturated 
is larger than the amount of saturates. And, the larger the better. The two 
numbers will not add up to the total amount of fat, because the margarines also 
contain monounsaturates. 
</P>
<P>
People often inquire about why margarines advertised as "rich in 
polyunsaturates" contain a more saturated fat, such as partially hydrogenated 
soybean oil, as the second ingredient. The explanation is simply that, without 
it, you would have liquid oil, not solid margarine. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I have always avoided buying meats packaged in heavy plastic wrap. While the 
price is often less than for meats in standard packaging, I have been put off 
by the unusually dark color. I assumed that it meant either that it was a lower 
grade of meat or that additives had been added to prolong freshness. While 
staying with a friend recently, she bought and served a large piece of 
vacuum-packed meat. It tasted perfectly fine, but before I'm sold on it I'd 
like an explanation for the color difference. 
</P>
<P>
A: The dark color indicates neither a quality difference nor the use of 
additives. It is the result of a lack of exposure of the meat to oxygen. 
</P>
<P>
The type of cuts you are describing are called subprimals. Whole beef carcasses 
are usually split into five large primal cuts, which are then divided into 
subprimals. Most beef is now cut into subprimals at the packing plant, 
vacuum-packed immediately and shipped to the supermarket. Those available 
directly to consumers are usually the best parts of those cuts, with much of 
the bone and other waste already trimmed. 
</P>
<P>
When the package is opened, the meat "blooms" -- turning the bright color with 
which you are familiar. Vacuum-packed meats do have an odor, described as sour 
or off when opened, but it disappears within an hour after opening. These meats 
have not been previously frozen, so they can be stored in the freezer as is or 
cut into smaller pieces and repackaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
